## Propagating Trace Context Across RabbitMQ

The key idea: inject the current `Activity` context into RabbitMQ message headers on publish, then extract and restore it on consume.

### Publisher (Service A)

```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;

// Create an ActivitySource for your service
static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceA");

// When publishing:
using var activity = Source.StartActivity("OrderPublished", ActivityKind.Producer);

var props = channel.CreateBasicProperties();
props.Headers ??= new Dictionary<string, object>();

// Inject W3C traceparent/tracestate into message headers
if (Activity.Current != null)
{
    props.Headers["traceparent"] = Activity.Current.Id!;
    props.Headers["tracestate"] = Activity.Current.TraceStateString ?? "";
}

channel.BasicPublish(exchange, routingKey, props, body);
```

### Consumer (Service B)

```csharp
static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceB");

// In your consumer callback:
var headers = ea.BasicProperties.Headers;

string? traceparent = null;
string? tracestate = null;

if (headers?.TryGetValue("traceparent", out var tp) == true)
    traceparent = Encoding.UTF8.GetString((byte[])tp);
if (headers?.TryGetValue("tracestate", out var ts) == true)
    tracestate = Encoding.UTF8.GetString((byte[])ts);

// Restore the parent context so the new activity links back
using var activity = Source.StartActivity(
    "OrderReceived",
    ActivityKind.Consumer,
    parentId: traceparent ?? "",
    tags: null,
    links: null);

if (activity != null && tracestate != null)
    activity.TraceStateString = tracestate;

// Process the message — this activity now shares the same TraceId
```

### Wire it up in `Program.cs` (both services)

```csharp
builder.Services.AddOpenTelemetry()
    .WithTracing(t => t
        .AddSource("ServiceA")   // or "ServiceB"
        .AddOtlpExporter());
```

### Why this works

| Concept | Detail |
|---|---|
| `traceparent` header | Carries the W3C trace ID + parent span ID |
| `ActivityKind.Producer/Consumer` | Tells the trace backend this is a messaging hop |
| `parentId` parameter | Links the consumer span to the producer's trace |

RabbitMQ headers store values as `byte[]`, hence the `Encoding.UTF8.GetString` on the consumer side. With this in place, your trace backend (Jaeger, Zipkin, etc.) will stitch both services into one end-to-end trace.
